@startuml fig-vlsm-allocation
'A4 Landscape
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false

title VLSM Allocation Example\nVariable Length Subnet Masking

rectangle "Network: 192.168.1.0/24 (256 addresses)" as main #F5F5F5 {
    rectangle "Dept A: 100 hosts\n192.168.1.0/25\n(128 addresses)" as a #BBDEFB
    
    rectangle "Dept B: 50 hosts\n192.168.1.128/26\n(64 addresses)" as b #C8E6C9
    
    rectangle "Dept C: 25 hosts\n192.168.1.192/27\n(32 addresses)" as c #FFE0B2
    
    rectangle "Links: 2 hosts each\n192.168.1.224/30\n192.168.1.228/30\n(4 addr each)" as links #E1BEE7
    
    rectangle "Reserved\n192.168.1.232/29" as res #ECEFF1
}

note bottom of main
    VLSM Steps:
    1. Sort requirements largest first
    2. Allocate largest subnet first
    3. Continue with remaining space
    4. Always allocate on proper boundary
    
    Boundary rule: Network address must be
    divisible by subnet size
end note

note right of a : Usable: .1-.126
note right of b : Usable: .129-.190
note right of c : Usable: .193-.222
note right of links : Point-to-point

